<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 10:18<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I295dd720630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Documentary and Demonstrative Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id721018c682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:18.</label.designator><headtext>Demonstrations</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Demonstrations conducted in the courtroom have long been held admissible so long as they fairly illustrate some relevant point evidence or contention of the parties.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6236c007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The trial court&apos;s discretion to allow courtroom demonstrations <page no="370"/>or experiments is broader than that for pretrial experiments, but the requirements are the same.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6236c017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Generally, the higher courts will uphold the trial court&apos;s decision regardless of whether it does not[<footnote.reference refid="Ic6236c027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] or does permit the demonstration.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic6236c037fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic6236c007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1909013806" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I5a20f8627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Southern Ry. Co. v. Brock, 132 Ga. 858, 64 S.E. 1083 (1909)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1983133041" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2146827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Metropolitan Property &amp; Liability Ins. Co. v. Shepherd, 166 Ga. App. 300, 304 S.E.2d 74 (1983)</cite.query>, held that the trial court properly allowed a courtroom demonstration in which a piece of carpet, which was taken from a home where a fire had occurred, was burned.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1984121548" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2194a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">McCulligh v. State, 169 Ga. App. 717, 314 S.E.2d 724 (1984)</cite.query>, held the trial court properly allowed a courtroom demonstration showing how the defendant could have scratched his arm when he reached through a screen door.<eos/><page no="370"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6236c017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="0280312591" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="I5a2209d07fc011ea988285db8533e975">McCormick on Evidence § 215 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6236c027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1933105052" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I5a227f027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hudson v. State, 46 Ga. App. 668, 168 S.E. 912 (1933)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1976136138" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a227f057fc011ea988285db8533e975">Reese v. State, 139 Ga. App. 630, 229 S.E.2d 111 (1976)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1987143050" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a227f087fc011ea988285db8533e975">Mathis v. State, 184 Ga. App. 455, 361 S.E.2d 856 (1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic6236c037fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1962127813" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2342527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Christian Const. Co. v. Wood, 104 Ga. App. 751, 123 S.E.2d 151 (1961)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1977135839" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2342557fc011ea988285db8533e975">Redwing Carriers, Inc. v. Knight, 143 Ga. App. 668, 239 S.E.2d 686 (1977)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="2003637872" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2342587fc011ea988285db8533e975">Roebuck v. State, 277 Ga. 200, 586 S.E.2d 651 (2003)</cite.query>); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1981137269" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a23425b7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Blount v. Moore, 159 Ga. App. 80, 282 S.E.2d 720 (1981)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1983133041" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a23425e7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Metropolitan Property &amp; Liability Ins. Co. v. Shepherd, 166 Ga. App. 300, 304 S.E.2d 74 (1983)</cite.query> (burning a piece of carpet); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1984121548" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2342617fc011ea988285db8533e975">McCulligh v. State, 169 Ga. App. 717, 314 S.E.2d 724 (1984)</cite.query> (sticking arm through screen door); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="1984132386" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2342647fc011ea988285db8533e975">Atkinson v. State, 170 Ga. App. 260, 316 S.E.2d 592 (1984)</cite.query> (demonstration of bolt cutters); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017216" w-serial-number="2037157100" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5a2342677fc011ea988285db8533e975">Crawford v. State, 297 Ga. 680, 777 S.E.2d 463 (2015)</cite.query> (allowing state to use rope to show act of strangulation).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 10:18<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
